The potentiodynamic polarization (PDP) curves for carbon steel in 0.5 M H2SO4 solution in the presence and absence of IL-CDs are shown in Fig. 7
                           . The presence of IL-CDs makes both the anodic and cathodic branches of the PDP curves move to lower current densities as compared to that of the uninhibited solution. Compared to the blank solution, the maximum corrosion potential (Ecorr
                           ) of the solution containing IL-CDs shift less than ± 85 mV, revealing that all the IL-CDs on the carbon steel surface belong to mixed-type inhibitors retarding both anodic and cathodic reaction.

Kinetic study of corrosion inhibition performance is of great importance. Electrochemical tests at different temperatures were performed in the absence and the presence of different concentrations of IL-CDs3, and the corrosion rate (CR
                        ) of carbon steel are shown in Table 8
                        .
